The social part can be completely interconnected with the opening of the living room door and the larger society can communicate comfortably without preserving the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, Gaudí's house also gained an unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles is also impressive, which includes an inner yard and lights.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs sun rays on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló house, which was assigned to the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
