In fact, it is a powerful software that simulating marches which the German company put on the market in 2007 for the purposes of a very remote car sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines at production plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision devices.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or to simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary errors and spending.
The PLM has facilitated the development of Canon, Sukhoi aircraft or the most famous Nissan commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens industrial division, explains that the use of this software device allowed Red Bull to perform "over a few hours, in almost real time" modification and improvement, which otherwise detects during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992 the stables employed on average 10 technicians who were able to perform no more than three or four improvements in one period.
Today, Red Bull is working on 180 highly qualified young professionals equipped with powerful information technology who analyze and suggest any type of modification of racing vehicles.
The manager of Siemens explained that PLM is capable of analysing and improving all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles except for the engine for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety components are being modified.
It is possible to convert changes from virtual reality to reality within less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using lasers and highly technologically advanced autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical capacity is the amount of $40 million representing the maximum that each Formula 1 team can issue for each period to improve its competitiveness.
Red Bull has established a race 50 km from London to design and manufacture its racing cars.
These are two buildings, which are restricted to visiting - especially to journalists.
Everything that's going on here is considered a "big secret."
The list of participants includes 580 people, including two pilots - the Vettela Champion and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull is in Formula 1 without doubt the fresh champion Sebastian Vettel.
However, other protagonists whose aid is priceless and unknown are hiding behind the immeasurable technological means that the brand of energy drinks has placed in their participation in racing circuits.
The head of production technology Steve Nevey claims that five years ago it was possible to say that the progress in research and development of vehicles contributed to the victory of 50% and the rest was the merit of the riders.
Currently, this ratio has changed and technology is worth the successes of 85%, while pilots contribute 15%.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer technology because they are "unforeseeable gladiators".
