The United States amends the rules on the issuance of visas
People will have to contact the Services Centres for Visas before interviewing the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting time will be reduced.
The process of discussing visas to the United States Embassy and consulates will change from 10 January 2011.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the visa applicant's centre (in short of English ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The staff of the ASC shall receive biometric information from the applicant and shall be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total costs of processing the visa will be lower, the fee for agreeing the meeting will no longer be payable, the second for processing the application and the other for delivery of the transport service document.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff remains unchanged: an amount corresponding to 140 dollars per tourist visa, $150 per visa cases with applications (including temporary staff visas) and $390 per visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to have an interview with a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Given that biometric information will be received in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with the Consultary Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who will apply for a visa at the consultants in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for a 26-dollar service.
For further information on the new procedure when applying for a visa, visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
